#compdef flow-8-midi
# ============================================================================
# flow-8-midi - cross-platform desktop MIDI
#                controller GUI for the
#                Behringer FLOW 8 mixer (Rust,
#                GPL-3.0)
#
# Author : Abel Rocha Espinosa (abelroes)
# Upstream: https://github.com/abelroes/flow-8-midi
# crates : flow-8-midi (binary: flow-8-midi)
#
# `flow-8-midi` is a cross-platform desktop GUI
# (built with the iced framework) for remotely
# controlling the Behringer FLOW 8 digital mixer
# via its USB MIDI interface or Bluetooth Low
# Energy MIDI profile. The FLOW 8 is a 8-channel
# portable digital mixer popular with streamers,
# podcasters, and small-venue musicians; its
# stock control software is Windows-only +
# limited in functionality. flow-8-midi provides:
#   - 8-channel mixer view (gain + level + pan +
#     compressor + low-cut + 4-band EQ + sends to
#     monitor mixes + sends to FX returns)
#   - FX page (reverb/delay/chorus parameter
#     control on the two onboard FX engines)
#   - EQ page (per-channel 4-band parametric EQ
#     with visual frequency-response curve)
#   - Sends page (per-channel send levels to
#     each monitor mix + FX bus)
#   - Snapshots page (save + recall full mixer
#     state via MIDI sysex)
#   - Settings page (MIDI device selection +
#     Bluetooth LE pairing)
#
# Connectivity:
#   - USB MIDI (standard USB MIDI class device)
#   - Bluetooth LE MIDI (Apple-defined BLE MIDI
#     profile)
#
# Implementation:
#   - iced 0.14 GUI framework (with tokio
#     async-IO backend)
#   - midir 0.10 for cross-platform MIDI I/O
#     (ALSA on Linux + CoreMIDI on macOS +
#     WinMM/WinRT on Windows)
#   - btleplug 0.11 for Bluetooth LE MIDI
#     connectivity
#   - Custom sysex parser for FLOW 8-specific
#     binary message formats (channel state
#     dumps + snapshot save/recall)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Linux-based studio/podcast/livestream
#     setups using the FLOW 8 as the audio
#     interface (the official Behringer software
#     is Windows-only)
#   - macOS users wanting a native desktop
#     controller (vs Behringer's Web-based UI)
#   - iPhone/iPad-free Bluetooth control of the
#     FLOW 8 from a laptop
#   - Streaming setups requiring scriptable
#     MIDI control (snapshots + named scene
#     recall via sysex)
#
# Usage:
#   flow-8-midi
#
# This binary takes no command-line flags - it
# launches the iced GUI window directly. All
# configuration (MIDI device selection, BLE
# pairing, preferred mixer view) happens through
# the GUI's settings page + is persisted to the
# OS-standard config directory:
#   - Linux: $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/flow-8-midi/
#   - macOS: ~/Library/Application Support/
#     flow-8-midi/
#   - Windows: %APPDATA%\flow-8-midi\
#
# Auxiliary binaries (declared as `[[bin]]`
# entries in Cargo.toml; built separately via
# `cargo build --bin <name>`):
#   - analyze_names              - debug tool for
#                                    sysex name
#                                    decoding
#   - calibrate                  - calibration
#                                    tool that
#                                    walks every
#                                    CC + sysex
#                                    parameter +
#                                    dumps
#                                    response
#                                    timing to
#                                    `calibration-
#                                    data/`
#   - digest                     - sysex message
#                                    digest /
#                                    hash tool
#
# These auxiliary binaries are not typically
# user-invoked but are useful for FLOW 8
# protocol reverse-engineering + firmware
# version compatibility testing.
#
# The midir lane is built on `midir = "^0.10.0"`
# with `features = ["winrt"]` (declared verbatim
# at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported by the `service::midi` module for
# cross-platform MIDI device enumeration +
# input/output connection + sysex message
# transmission), the canonical Rust cross-
# platform MIDI library by Patrick Klein
# (Boddlnagg) - github.com/Boddlnagg/midir.
#
# Patrick Klein's midir is the de-facto canonical
# Rust MIDI library:
#   - 700+ reverse-deps on crates.io
#   - Cross-platform MIDI I/O abstraction
#     (Linux ALSA + macOS CoreMIDI + Windows
#     WinMM + Windows WinRT + JACK + WebMIDI
#     for wasm32)
#   - Stable callback-based input API + send-
#     based output API
#   - Virtual port support (Linux ALSA + macOS
#     CoreMIDI)
#   - Sysex (System Exclusive) message support
#   - Bindings auto-generated from the C-level
#     OS APIs via bindgen
#   - Thread-safe device handles
#
# midir's distinguishing position vs alternatives:
#   - midir (Klein): canonical; cross-platform;
#     THIS AXIS
#   - rust-midi: deprecated predecessor
#   - portmidi-rs: PortMIDI bindings (alternative
#     C library; less actively maintained)
#   - midi-control: higher-level MIDI message
#     parsing (often used with midir for I/O)
#
# Patrick Klein's broader Rust ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - midir (canonical Rust MIDI; THIS AXIS)
#   - rust-bindgen contributor (the C-to-Rust
#     binding-generator that midir uses for OS
#     API access)
#   - Various smaller utility crates around
#     real-time audio + MIDI integration
#
# Klein's role in Rust is *specialized real-time
# audio / MIDI infrastructure* - similar to
# zonyitoo (rust-ini + Shadowsocks + bson) in
# the *specialized protocol implementation*
# canonical-author cluster.
#
# flow-8-midi uses midir in `service::midi`
# module to:
#   1. Enumerate MIDI input + output devices
#      (`midir::MidiInput::new()?.ports()` for
#      listing, `port_name()` for human-readable
#      names)
#   2. Connect to a selected device
#      (`midir::MidiInput::connect(...)`)
#   3. Send Control Change (CC) messages for
#      real-time parameter control (level, EQ,
#      send, mute, solo)
#   4. Send System Exclusive (sysex) messages
#      for snapshot save/recall + full mixer
#      state dumps
#   5. Receive incoming MIDI from the FLOW 8
#      (mixer-side knob movements + button
#      presses surface as MIDI back to the
#      controller for two-way state sync)
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 269 :: MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital
#              Interface) device I/O libraries
#              (cross-platform MIDI 1.0 spec
#              + USB MIDI Class + sysex message
#              handling)
# Round 1505 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 269
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : Boddlnagg/midir              - Patrick
#                                              Klein's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Rust MIDI
#                                              library;
#                                              cross-
#                                              platform;
#                                              ALSA +
#                                              CoreMIDI +
#                                              WinMM +
#                                              WinRT +
#                                              JACK +
#                                              WebMIDI
#   Go      : gomidi/midi                  - Marc
#                                              Rene
#                                              Arns'
#                                              canonical
#                                              Go MIDI
#                                              library;
#                                              wraps
#                                              rtmidi C
#                                              library
#                                              via cgo
#   TS/Node : justinlatimer/node-midi       - Justin
#                                              Latimer's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Node MIDI
#                                              library;
#                                              also
#                                              wraps
#                                              rtmidi C
#                                              library;
#                                              native
#                                              addon
#                                              via
#                                              node-gyp
#
# MIDI is a *spec-bound* axis - the MIDI 1.0
# specification (MMA Technical Standard 1.0,
# 1983; updated to MIDI 2.0 in 2020) defines the
# wire-format protocol:
#   - 31,250 baud serial (over MIDI DIN-5)
#   - USB MIDI Class (USB-MIDI 1.0 spec, 1999)
#   - Network MIDI (RTP MIDI / AppleMIDI, RFC
#     6295)
#   - Bluetooth LE MIDI (Apple-defined GATT
#     profile)
#
# Each canonical library provides cross-platform
# abstractions over the OS-specific MIDI APIs:
#   - Linux: ALSA sequencer + JACK MIDI
#   - macOS: CoreMIDI
#   - Windows: WinMM (legacy) + WinRT (modern)
#   - Web: Web MIDI API
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - midir (Rust): pure-Rust MIDI abstraction
#     with bindgen-generated OS bindings; no
#     C/C++ dependency
#   - gomidi (Go): wraps the rtmidi C++ library
#     via cgo
#   - node-midi (Node): wraps the rtmidi C++
#     library via node-gyp native addon
#
# Notable that both Go + Node lanes wrap the
# same underlying C/C++ library (rtmidi by Gary
# P. Scavone). The Rust lane is the *only* lane
# with a pure-language implementation. This is
# the *Rust-as-only-pure-impl* pattern, parallel
# to:
#   - resvg (Rust SVG renderer; vs Cairo + libxml
#     in other lanes at Axis 264)
#   - tiny-skia (Rust 2D rasterization; vs Skia
#     C++ in other lanes)
#   - rustls (Rust TLS; vs OpenSSL in other
#     lanes)
#
# Cross-language interop at the MIDI message
# byte level - all three libraries send +
# receive byte-identical MIDI messages on the
# wire. Sysex compatibility is similarly
# universal since the message format is defined
# at the byte level.
#
# Axis 269 opens with the Rust slot at Boddlnagg/
# midir, anchoring Klein's specialized-protocol
# canonical position. Subsequent rounds will
# visit the Go (gomidi/midi) + TS/Node
# (justinlatimer/node-midi) canonicals.
#
# Use case spectrum for this axis:
#   - flow-8-midi (Rust, midir): cross-platform
#     desktop MIDI controller for the Behringer
#     FLOW 8 digital mixer
#
# MIDI tooling spans the entire music-production
# ecosystem: DAWs (Ableton Live + FL Studio +
# Logic Pro + Reaper + Ardour) + standalone
# instruments + hardware controllers + MIDI
# sequencers + algorithmic composition tools.
# The MIDI 1.0 spec's longevity (40+ years
# since 1983) makes it one of the most-
# implemented protocol axes in computing.
# ============================================================================

_flow-8-midi() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]'
}

_flow-8-midi "$@"
